insta_description:
0052. Now we are all heroes. Ahora todos somos h√©roes.
__It has been quite a few days since my last post, I was quite busy readjusting from the States back to Spain, and on top of that, I lost access to this account too‚Äînot great. Now, in these strange and difficult days for all, I thought that it would be nice to share this cutie that I don‚Äôt only like, but I also believe it may well capture the kind of attitude that we all have been called to have or to put in practice. In this painting, unlike other more dynamic, intrepid, triumphant and even sexier images of Superman, the hero stands still and quiet. His fists close and ready to beat, his arms and legs firm and his gaze attentive, Superman is alert yet calm. This image of the comic hero echoes the dignity and restraint of classical portraiture. Still, the superhero in his rather ordinary posture looks more like one of us, just like a simple man ready to face whatever may be ahead of him. Now we all are our heroes, we fight together and protect each other. I would love to dedicate this post to the workers of our health systems, and specially to my friend @manuelalejandro.pr who is doing an incredible job in Seville.  Much encouragement! Stay strong!
__Ahora todos somos nuestros h√©roes. Dedicado a los trabajadores y trabajadoras de nuestro sistema de salud, en especial para mi amigo que esta haciendo ahora un trabajo incre√≠ble, mucho √°nimo!

One of our central values at Oasis Dental Arts is that we want to have good relationships with our patients. Scripps Ranch dentist Dr. Ramin Goshtasbi (you can call him ‚ÄúDr. G‚Äù) makes this a central focus of our practice. Why is this so important? Because having a good relationship with your dentist can improve your quality of care in many ways.‚Å†
‚Å†
We Know Your History‚Å†
Knowing your history can help us understand how oral disease tends to progress for you‚Äìthis can be highly variable, depending on your genetics and your oral health habits. This helps us to make better recommendations for the right approach to your dental care, such a whether you need a simple cleaning with modified hygiene or if it‚Äôs time to do a deep cleaning.‚Å†
‚Å†
You Develop Trust‚Å†
Another important part of quality dental care is being able to trust your dentist. Some people have a problem with this: there‚Äôs a prevailing sense that when a dentist recommends treatment, they‚Äôre just trying to get your money. Getting to know your dentist over time will reveal that their true concern is your health and happiness, and that all recommended treatments are intended for that goal. That will help you get more comfortable choosing the right treatment for you.‚Å†
‚Å†
We Look Forward to Meeting You‚Å†
If you‚Äôre looking for a dentist in Scripps Ranch that is focused on giving you the best dental care through developing quality relationships, please call (858) 271-1010 today for an appointment with Dr. G at Oasis Dental Arts.‚Å†

accessibility_caption: Photo by Henri Holbrook on March 17, 2020. Image may contain: tree, sky, outdoor and nature
insta_description:
I was also lucky enough to see (and start) a lot of amazing fire behavior in 2019. We were able to burn a few hundred acres within our parks, in a wide variety of habitats and weather conditions throughout fall.
~
#1 Burning in mixed hardwood forest on a steep slope. Notice the rings of flame creeping up the trunk of the bay laurel as the feather moss burns off. 
#2 Understory burn in a far overstocked douglas-fir forest that was most likely an open patch of grass 40 years ago.

#3 An accidental video during some very mild burning conditions.

#4 A backing fire in a grassland. This is what is used to keep flames within the control lines on prescribed and wild fires. When firefighters say 'fighting fire with fire' this is what they mean.

#5 A head fire on a steep slope in warm conditions. This looks wild, but it was neccassary to achieve our goal of killing doug-fir trees that are choking out our prairies. When prescribed fire is done right, only the youngest and weakest trees are killed, leaving more space and resources for the legacy trees and historic ecosystems to thrive. 
#6 and #7 My handywork with a driptorch :)))
~

insta_description:
Sometimes, I feel like I am in an episode of The Blue Planet, exploring the deep dark of our world. I am overcome with graditute that I am able to go on these deep sea adventures and experience an ecosystem few will ever see first hand or even learn about. I had no idea all this strange, alien-like life existed here in San Diego, and I have been here my whole life. I am so cold down there but my heart is full, I can hang out with my sea slugs and Gorgonians. 
This is the Gorgonian Forest in La Jolla Canyon, 115 feet deep. There use to be a lot more gorgonians here. Featured is the purple gorgonians, parchment worms, an orange featherduster worm, a corymorph hydroid with a opalecent nudibranch, a sea clown triopha (sea slug), and a chestnut cowry snail.

It was a 2 way street and it had no railing on the side (which made it a little scary) and there were a few times where cars were coming in the opposite direction. Eventually, we got out of the mountains and made it back to the main road. Oh, and at the end of all of this we see a coyote. üò≤

accessibility_caption: Photo by Kimberly Stewart in Memphis, Tennessee with @grapejuice08. Image may contain: 2 people, people standing, tree, shoes, plant, outdoor and nature
insta_description:
Little did I know that this last family trip to Memphis a couple weeks ago would be my last trip for awhile. Love you, sissy! @grapejuice08 THE QUARANTEAM life. (this term was stolen from my roommate because it shows that even if we are isolated from each other, we can still support each other & be a team! üò¨)
.
‚ö°Ô∏è It‚Äôs been a whirlwind of a year for everyone, but we should all take this time to show empathy, compassion, & love because it is something we can all relate to each other on & tho it is affecting us all it can connect us as well! The more we come together, the stronger we become. I‚Äôm not one who enjoys social isolation or quarantine because I am such an extrovert & love being around people, but I‚Äôm glad to be forced to the other side sometimes because I have a tendency to run myself until I‚Äôm literally on the ground, lol. We need the Yin AND the yang to be stable & I have been getting so much done that I would normally put off. I work from home so my life hasn‚Äôt changed much on that front, but as a salesperson, it becomes an extreme stress point when ALL of your deals are on hold indefinitely Ouch. lol Here are some ideas below for what to do.üí°
.
‚ö°Ô∏èMake sure to do one type of work out a day. It helps to release endorphins & boost your immune system. My yoga studio, @soulplay.yoga is streaming all their classes so we won‚Äôt miss out. This is one of my many reasons I love them so much! You can sign up even if you don‚Äôt go there!üßòüèº‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è
.
‚ö°Ô∏è Check out some new music & support your artists. Having a dance session is good for the soul and to let loose while you are working or even if you are out of work. This is the way I take breaks everyday since I work from home. üé∂üéµ
.
‚ö°Ô∏èIf you can rescue an animal, there are so many that need you & you would have plenty of time to acclimate them into your home! This also would be great if you have kids because they can have a buddy.üê∂
.
‚ö°Ô∏èOrder some crayons, color pencils, markers & a coloring book and your set. Me and one of my besties are going to have a facetime date since I can‚Äôt be with her. It‚Äôs so therapeutic and fun as an adult. .
‚ö°Ô∏è Get your taxes done. I had been putting it off forever & it felt so good!

insta_description:
1. Wake up at the same time everyday
I set my work schedule based on business hours. In order to set up my day accordingly it is so important that I wake up at the same time everyday. 
2. Set up a professional workspace 
I have to be honest, I live in New York City and don‚Äôt have enough space to have my own ‚Äúpersonal office‚Äù at home. So I created a small workspace in a section of my room that has my desk, laptop, office supplies, and cute plant üå± üòâ This allows be to stay focused and not get distracted by that warm cozy bed. 
3. Get dressed 
There have been days where I just sat it in my PJs all day. But I find it so much more helpful to actually get dressed for the day. Even wearing a t-shirt and a pair of jeans will make you feel like a #girlboss with so many things to do. 
4. Create a to do list
Creating a list always helps me to stay on track. There are so many distractions at home from my cute üê∂ to Netflix. A list will help you to stay focused.

5. Take breaks
This is so important for days that you are so busy you forget to eat lunch! I try to take a break often even if it‚Äôs just to go outside for some fresh air. Breaks can give you clarity which is great to get that think tank going.

6.Eat balanced meals
Since my days can get so hectic, I try to have my meals prepped in advance. This helps me to keep my stress levels down because I don‚Äôt have to worry about what to eat, preparing my meals, or spending unnecessary money. 
7. Set a clear schedule 
If your day starts at 9 make sure to end at 5. It is so easy to get caught up in a project that you forget to end your day. This can make it difficult to separate your ‚Äúwork life‚Äù from your ‚Äúhome life‚Äù. So make sure you set clear hours and set boundaries for yourself. .

insta_description:
Who knew that the excitement the world had leading up to a new decade would come to a screeching halt by March, literally, and that 2020 would be the year we would be sitting in our living rooms rekindling old hobbies, and discovering new talents from the discomfort of our couches?

I anticipated spending most of the year abroad, but decided over the past week that travel can wait, because lives are at stake. Delaying all trips until we flatten the curve and things are back to normal - hopefully by summer, but as long as it takes.

On the flip side, I‚Äôve been able to have more conversations with the dog, edit travel footage that has never seen the light of day, and have more time to plan upcoming trips that were a bit rushed.

Going to try to keep things light on my feed and stories since I know you‚Äôre already inundated with stress and negative news.

How about you? How are you doing? What talents or good things are you discovering out of this social distancing?
.

RESIDENTIAL FINANCING

If you are purchasing multi-unit investment properties, the type of loan will depend on the properties. If you are buying 1-4 unit properties, conventional residential financing applies. If you are looking at 5+ units, then commercial financing applies.

Often times, residential financing will give you better terms than commercial financing. For example, you can get a 30-year fixed mortgage with residential financing. A commercial loan may offer a fixed period, but it may vary after the fixed period and could contain a pre-payment penalty. The costs are usually higher on a commercial loan, too.

We had a client who wanted to purchase 5 4-plexes as one transaction. We shopped both commercial and residential loans, and found that we could obtain better financing if there were 5 separate transactions for each 4-plex. We were able to secure 30-year fixed mortgages for each 4-plex, rather than a variable rate commercial loan for the entire project.

If you are considering purchasing multi-unit investment properties, contact us and we can help you structure the financing.

We‚Äôve been asked to ‚Äúshelter in place‚Äù here in San Francisco (as has most of the Bay Area) but are still encouraged to go on walks, hikes, and stay active within reason. So off to Golden Gate Park we go with our trusty and tasty @drinkomission beer in hand (and a 6 foot safe space around us)! Omission was started in early 2000s because the brewmasters wife was diagnosed with celiac disease and he wanted a beer that they could both enjoy! They are super transparent about their gluten removal processes, and even have the test results from every batch available on their website. How a awesome is that?! insta_description: Sitting inside ùêåùêöùê†ùê†ùê¢ùêû ùêåùêúùêÜùêöùê´ùê´ùê≤‚Äôùê¨ on 3/10/20, enjoying a pint of Guinness and a little Tullamore Dew. It struck me that, the only place I enjoy openly talking politics with strangers, is in an Irish pub. Not on trains or subways. And definitely not on social media. The Irish pub holds a special place in my heart. Rarely can you find a setting without judgement or prejudice. But the Irish know all too well that while we all have opinions and beliefs, ultimately you have to play the hand you‚Äôre dealt. An older man sat on the other side of the bar with his adoring wife, slightly distracted by the rugby game on the television, professing his admiration for the bar owners and staff for being open. ‚ÄúSurely we‚Äôll be quarantined in the near future.‚Äù ‚ÄúYou really think so?‚Äù, I said. ‚ÄúAbsolutely. There‚Äôs really no question about it. You look at our response. You look at our local government in San Francisco.‚Äù In a somewhat Connor McGregor moment he said, ‚Äúlet‚Äôs be honest, we‚Äôre all fooked.‚Äù At the time I laughed and so did the few other patrons at the bar top. But where most men would leave that to be their final thought, this Irishmen removed his hat sat up and said something along the lines of, ‚Äúgentlemen, what an honor to be in this beautiful bar in this beautiful city surrounded by a few good friends. May we always remember these times.‚Äù I sat up and walked over to cheers. I said in response, ‚Äúùêíùê•√°ùê¢ùêßùê≠ùêû‚Äù. Not sensing the irony of my toast at the time. As I sit here in isolation I think of that man. That man who‚Äôs name I never got. Who called me his friend. accessibility_caption: Photo by KC Turner Presents in San Francisco, California. Image may contain: 1 person, standing, hat and night
insta_description:
Which do you prefer? ‚ÄúCanceled‚Äù or ‚ÄúCancelled‚Äù? It‚Äôs a word I‚Äôm getting very familiar with lately. I‚Äôm leaning on the double ‚ÄúL‚Äù.
üéºüéº
I'm writing to you from my living room in San Francisco where I stay hunkered down unraveling 6 months+ of work: scheduling, production, tour routing, promotion... you name it - everything that goes into putting on a concert. At this point I'm postponing or cancelling most every KC Turner Presents show from now through mid-May. If you have tickets to any of the shows that are postponed, PLEASE try your best to hang on to your tickets as we work hard to reschedule the dates. Of course, if the new date doesn't work for you, or a show is cancelled altogether, refunds will be offered. Please be patient with the ticketing companies as they are overwhelmed with thousands of concerts being cancelled or postponed all at once. üéºüéº
I'm trying my very best to keep my chin up. Our 7th annual Cookout Concert Series at HopMonk Novato begins in the summer and is still on as planned. The full lineup has yet to be announced. One way you can really help myself, the venue, and most importantly the artists is by purchasing your tickets as far in advance as you're able. Knowing we all have sold out shows to look forward to will keep our determination and our will strong, and give us all hope that the dust will settle and we can all be together in one space again. üéºüéº
My heart and thoughts are with all of you during this disruptive time in our lives. This is uncharted territory, but I know we‚Äôll figure it out because our music community is strong! Stay safe. Stay healthy.
üéºüéº
We are ALL in this together!
üéºüéº

We want to reassure our patients that we are closely following all daily and hourly updates regarding the COVID-19 pandemic from the CDC and local, county, and state authorities. We are dedicated to the safety and health of our patients and staff. We want to share some of the added precautions we are taking at this time and ask for your patience and understanding. Safety is our top priority.
.
We are following the highest standards for cleaning and sterilization. We routinely clean and disinfect every exam room, countertop, and doorknobs before and after each patient visit. All instruments are sterilized and packaged, and all medical equipment wiped down with hospital-grade disinfectants. Elective procedures are still being performed in our outpatient surgical center, which has a private and safe environment where traffic is very limited. The sterilization and cleaning team we bring in before and after each procedure is a professional cleaning team that uses the same standards as the hospital.
.
At this time, we are continuing to operate as usual, but we will keep you posted should that change. We are making every effort to be proactive and cautious during this time. We ask that you alert us before your appointment if you are experiencing any of the following symptoms: fever, cough, shortness of breath and breathing difficulties or any flu-like symptoms, and we will make every effort to accommodate your rescheduling requests.
.

insta_description:
Happy St. Patricks Day! Cauliflower is in season this month! Did you know there is orange, purple, and green colored cauliflower??!
.
.
Enjoy this Corned Beef and Cauliflower Hash recipe (via @wickedstuffed)
.
Ingredients:
3 cups cooked corned beef
1 head of chopped fresh cauliflower
1/2 yellow onion, chopped
1 tbsp olive oil
1 tsp cajun seasoning
salt and pepper to taste
Optional: 4 eggs (Just be sure to add net carbs if you do!)
Garnish: Fresh chopped parsley

Directions:
1. In a medium skillet, heat olive oil over medium heat.
2. Meanwhile, in a bowl, add 1/2 inch of water, and then chopped cauliflower. Microwave for 4 minutes (or steam how you traditionally like to steam veggies)
3. While the cauliflower is steaming, add the onions to the skillet to brown.
4. Let cook for one minute, then add 2 tbsp of water. When water reduces, add another tbsp and keep adding while cauliflower steams (this helps soften and caramelize the onions.)
5. Once cauliflower is done steaming, let sit for two minutes.
6. Add cauliflower and cajun seasoning to the skillet and mix. Let meld together for 5-10 minutes until desired softness, then add cooked corned beef and toss until hot.
7. Add salt and pepper to taste. Garnish with freshly chopped parsley, and top with fried eggs if you desire.
.
.

Amid the Coronavirus pandemic; LTWC is accepting injured and orphaned wildlife. The LTWC animal care team is taking steps to keep our team safe while remaining open for animal intake and rehabilitation. .
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
If you find an orphaned or injured animal call the center at 530.577.2273. 
Please do not come to the center, call to discuss safe drop off protocols with our staff. .
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
We are asking that the public, rescuers, and volunteers do not stop by before calling; as we are practicing social distancing to the best of our ability.  In an attempt to not overwhelm our very limited staff with phone calls, please email sally@ltwc.org with any non urgent questions or concerns. .
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
In order to continue to serve our community,  and our wildlife population, LTWC will be operating over the next several weeks with staff only. Our priority is to keep our animal care team healthy and safe so they can continue to focus on caring for our residents. .
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
The LTWC board is so grateful for our animal care team, volunteers and donors. Thank you so much for your support.  We could not operate without you!  We will continue to communicate with you all via social media. 
Stay safe and healthy.

insta_description:
Happy St. Patrick‚Äôs Day from the great indoors üçÄüè° Today is a day where many of us would typically go out and enjoy merriment together in groups, but this time it‚Äôs different. We‚Äôre in a most unusual time, and we all need love and support through the uncertainty and isolation. Thank goodness for our online resources to keep our interactions going as much as possible. I know many of you are stressed due to either health concerns, family concerns, isolation concerns, or financial concerns due to lost work. In difficult times (and not difficult times), I find that meditation, and simply practicing breathing and mindfulness goes a long way toward reducing anxieties and stress.
.
.
@jessica.coffman and I recently started a music meditation company together called Evergreen Meditations. We create musical soundscapes with nature sounds, singing bowls, a meditation guide (voice) and my favorite, the electric bass. We make completely customized meditations, but we do offer an ever-growing number of free meditations on our website, which I have a link to in my bio, plus spelled out below. If you‚Äôre interested in a custom meditation designed for your needs, we‚Äôre offering a deep discount on those with the code EVERGREENFRIENDSANDFAM. Copy and paste that into the discount code section on our site! Also please feel free to DM me with any questions, or if you just need someone to chat with ü§ó
.
.
.
Stay safe and healthy out there! Remember to wash your hands often and keep all common areas with others clean and sanitized. Contact your loved ones often. Help others in need as much as possible. Continue to pursue your calling in life while there is more time to do so! I send you all peace, light and love now, and for always. Please reach out to me if you need someone to talk to!
.
.

accessibility_caption: Photo by KC Turner Presents in San Francisco, California. Image may contain: 1 person, standing, hat and night
insta_description:
Which do you prefer? ‚ÄúCanceled‚Äù or ‚ÄúCancelled‚Äù? It‚Äôs a word I‚Äôm getting very familiar with lately. I‚Äôm leaning on the double ‚ÄúL‚Äù.
üéºüéº
I'm writing to you from my living room in San Francisco where I stay hunkered down unraveling 6 months+ of work: scheduling, production, tour routing, promotion... you name it - everything that goes into putting on a concert. At this point I'm postponing or cancelling most every KC Turner Presents show from now through mid-May. If you have tickets to any of the shows that are postponed, PLEASE try your best to hang on to your tickets as we work hard to reschedule the dates. Of course, if the new date doesn't work for you, or a show is cancelled altogether, refunds will be offered. Please be patient with the ticketing companies as they are overwhelmed with thousands of concerts being cancelled or postponed all at once. üéºüéº
I'm trying my very best to keep my chin up. Our 7th annual Cookout Concert Series at HopMonk Novato begins in the summer and is still on as planned. The full lineup has yet to be announced. One way you can really help myself, the venue, and most importantly the artists is by purchasing your tickets as far in advance as you're able. Knowing we all have sold out shows to look forward to will keep our determination and our will strong, and give us all hope that the dust will settle and we can all be together in one space again. üéºüéº
My heart and thoughts are with all of you during this disruptive time in our lives. This is uncharted territory, but I know we‚Äôll figure it out because our music community is strong! Stay safe. Stay healthy.
üéºüéº
We are ALL in this together!

insta_description:
We want to reassure our patients that we are closely following all daily and hourly updates regarding the COVID-19 pandemic from the CDC and local, county, and state authorities. We are dedicated to the safety and health of our patients and staff. We want to share some of the added precautions we are taking at this time and ask for your patience and understanding. Safety is our top priority.
.
We are following the highest standards for cleaning and sterilization. We routinely clean and disinfect every exam room, countertop, and doorknobs before and after each patient visit. All instruments are sterilized and packaged, and all medical equipment wiped down with hospital-grade disinfectants. Elective procedures are still being performed in our outpatient surgical center, which has a private and safe environment where traffic is very limited. The sterilization and cleaning team we bring in before and after each procedure is a professional cleaning team that uses the same standards as the hospital.
.
At this time, we are continuing to operate as usual, but we will keep you posted should that change. We are making every effort to be proactive and cautious during this time. We ask that you alert us before your appointment if you are experiencing any of the following symptoms: fever, cough, shortness of breath and breathing difficulties or any flu-like symptoms, and we will make every effort to accommodate your rescheduling requests.
.
Please call (805) 373-7073 or email morgan@doctorazar.com if you would like to schedule your next visit via video conferencing. Thank you for your continued trust and confidence.  #AzarPlasticSurgery

insta_description:
Happy St. Patricks Day! Cauliflower is in season this month! Did you know there is orange, purple, and green colored cauliflower??!
.
.
Enjoy this Corned Beef and Cauliflower Hash recipe (via @wickedstuffed)
.
Ingredients:
3 cups cooked corned beef
1 head of chopped fresh cauliflower
1/2 yellow onion, chopped
1 tbsp olive oil
1 tsp cajun seasoning
salt and pepper to taste
Optional: 4 eggs (Just be sure to add net carbs if you do!)
Garnish: Fresh chopped parsley

Directions:
1. In a medium skillet, heat olive oil over medium heat.
2. Meanwhile, in a bowl, add 1/2 inch of water, and then chopped cauliflower. Microwave for 4 minutes (or steam how you traditionally like to steam veggies)
3. While the cauliflower is steaming, add the onions to the skillet to brown.
4. Let cook for one minute, then add 2 tbsp of water. When water reduces, add another tbsp and keep adding while cauliflower steams (this helps soften and caramelize the onions.)
5. Once cauliflower is done steaming, let sit for two minutes.
6. Add cauliflower and cajun seasoning to the skillet and mix. Let meld together for 5-10 minutes until desired softness, then add cooked corned beef and toss until hot.
7. Add salt and pepper to taste. Garnish with freshly chopped parsley, and top with fried eggs if you desire.
.
.

insta_description:
Amid the Coronavirus pandemic; LTWC is accepting injured and orphaned wildlife. The LTWC animal care team is taking steps to keep our team safe while remaining open for animal intake and rehabilitation. 
If you find an orphaned or injured animal call the center at 530.577.2273. 
Please do not come to the center, call to discuss safe drop off protocols with our staff. 
We are asking that the public, rescuers, and volunteers do not stop by before calling; as we are practicing social distancing to the best of our ability.  In an attempt to not overwhelm our very limited staff with phone calls, please email sally@ltwc.org with any non urgent questions or concerns. 
In order to continue to serve our community,  and our wildlife population, LTWC will be operating over the next several weeks with staff only. Our priority is to keep our animal care team healthy and safe so they can continue to focus on caring for our residents. The LTWC board is so grateful for our animal care team, volunteers and donors. Thank you so much for your support.  We could not operate without you!  We will continue to communicate with you all via social media. 
Stay safe and healthy.
